1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:01,263
Day 6.

2
00:00:01,263 --> 00:00:03,722
I lost 31 dollars.

3
00:00:03,722 --> 00:00:10,972
Then I found something worse — the 90 percent win rate I'd been citing in public all week was basically fiction.

4
00:00:10,972 --> 00:00:12,458
I can't code.

5
00:00:12,458 --> 00:00:14,527
9 years in crypto.

6
00:00:14,527 --> 00:00:16,638
AI trades my thousand.

7
00:00:16,638 --> 00:00:17,944
Day 6.

8
00:00:17,944 --> 00:00:20,208
The bot hit a stop loss.

9
00:00:20,208 --> 00:00:23,430
Single trade loss of 31 dollars.

10
00:00:23,430 --> 00:00:26,277
First real loss of the experiment.

11
00:00:26,277 --> 00:00:28,291
I sat down to review.

12
00:00:28,291 --> 00:00:33,527
On a whim I stretched the backtest window from 5 days to 13 months.

13
00:00:33,527 --> 00:00:36,305
Same strategy — 13 months.

14
00:00:36,305 --> 00:00:38,902
Minus 46 percent return.

15
00:00:38,902 --> 00:00:41,930
Minus 56 percent max drawdown.

16
00:00:41,930 --> 00:00:50,319
Translation — the 90 percent win rate I'd been proud of for a week was a number hiding in the narrowest possible window.

17
00:00:50,319 --> 00:00:52,013
Not dishonest.

18
00:00:52,013 --> 00:00:53,722
Just incomplete.

19
00:00:53,722 --> 00:00:57,388
And incomplete when money's involved means — wrong.

20
00:00:57,388 --> 00:01:00,236
You know what your proudest number usually looks like?

21
00:01:00,236 --> 00:01:04,263
It's usually hiding in the corner you don't want to stretch.

22
00:01:04,263 --> 00:01:08,375
Stretching the window is the scariest thing you can do to yourself.

23
00:01:08,375 --> 00:01:10,666
Your number might survive.

24
00:01:10,666 --> 00:01:12,055
It might not.

25
00:01:12,055 --> 00:01:13,875
You don't know till you look.

26
00:01:13,875 --> 00:01:14,902
I looked.

27
00:01:14,902 --> 00:01:16,583
It didn't survive.

28
00:01:16,583 --> 00:01:20,902
Day 7 tomorrow — I decided to tear the whole thing apart.

29
00:01:20,902 --> 00:01:22,333
Follow along.

